# Phase 6 вЂ” Install Capacitor

Install Capacitor early so your application is mobile-ready from the beginning. This installs the current Capacitor 8 line.

```bash
npm install @capacitor/core
npm install -D @capacitor/cli
npm install @capacitor/android
```

Verify the installation:

```bash
npx cap --version
```

Initialize Capacitor:

```bash
npx cap init
```

Example:

```text
App Name:
MyApp

App ID:
com.example.myapp
```

This generates the `capacitor.config.ts` configuration file.

> **Note:** `webDir` must point to the folder containing your production web build. If you are using a static export (`output: "export"`), Next.js generates this folder as `out/` after running `npm run build`. If your app relies on SSR/Server Actions, see Phase 8 вЂ” you cannot statically export it, and `webDir` should instead point at wherever your deployed web app is served from (Capacitor will load it as a remote URL rather than bundling it locally).

Create the Android project:

```bash
npx cap add android
```

> Capacitor 8 requires **Android Studio Otter (2025.2.1)+** and **JDK 21**. If your Android Studio is older, run the AGP Upgrade Assistant (`Tools в†’ AGP Upgrade Assistant`) before opening the generated `android/` project.

---

# Phase 7 вЂ” Configure Capacitor

Edit `capacitor.config.ts`:

```ts
import { CapacitorConfig } from "@capacitor/cli";

const config: CapacitorConfig = {
  appId: "com.example.myapp",
  appName: "MyApp",
  webDir: "out",
};

export default config;
```

---

# Phase 8 вЂ” Configure Next.js (Static Export Only)

If your application is intended to run entirely as a static site inside Capacitor, update `next.config.ts`:

```ts
import type { NextConfig } from "next";

const nextConfig: NextConfig = {
  output: "export",
  trailingSlash: true,
  images: {
    unoptimized: true,
  },
};

export default nextConfig;
```

> **Important:** If your application uses Server-Side Rendering (SSR), Server Actions, Route Handlers that need a live server, or Cache Components, keep the default Next.js configuration instead of enabling `output: "export"` вЂ” these features are incompatible with static export and Capacitor would need to load the app from a deployed URL instead of bundling it locally.

